\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f0\fs32\lang9 Shield of Faith - User Guide\par
\b\fs28 WORK IN PROGRESS\fs24\par
\b0 This tool is intended to be free, disability friendly and easily understood. It is particularly intended to be useful to those who struggle with the light from their computer monitor.\par
\ul Feedback on what works and doesn't work is appreciated.\ulnone\par
(Ready made solutions and improvements are also appreciated, though I will only publish what I can verify as safe and sound.)\par
The product has \ul basic functionality \ulnone at this point. For usefulness to more people, it needs to be customizable with colouring and font sizes. I hope to be able to deliver that eventually.\par
\b\fs28 BASIC FUNCTIONALITY\b0\par
\fs24 This program covers the screen with a translucent window.\par
The button with the shield icon hides or shows that window, and you have a clickable bar (you can also use arrows or click buttons on its ends) to adjust the intensity. This helps darken the screen, reducing discomfort from the brighter colours, especially when they occur next to darker ones.\par
\b One instance of Shield of Faith \b0 can only cover one monitor at a time. You can change which one by moving the control window to the target monitor and click "move shield to this monitor".\par
\b\fs28 BASIC FUNCTIONALITY \b0 - \fs24 ShaderGlass.exe\par
A similar effect can be achieved by running a version of ShaderGlass.exe, modified to be controlled via this program. You start/show and hide that program using the button that either says "Shader Glass app" or shows the ShaderGlass program icon (a monitor).\par
ShaderGlass uses advanced graphics processing. Shield of Faith uses it to allow you to darken the screen with options to darken some colour components more than others.\par
The effect on the screen's colour is slightly different from the one achieved by covering everything with a translucent window.\par
\b One instance of Shield of Faith\b0  can only run one Shader Glass application at a time. You can adjust the location (and gain easy access to menus) of Shader Glass by clicking Window mode in Shield of Faith. You should be able to move Shader Glass to the desired monitor and return it to fullscreen with the same button. (I can't test as I have only one monitor.)\par
\b\fs28 WARNING\fs24\par
ShaderGlass\b0  is not developed or maintained by me, but I did examine and use the program a fair bit without issue before making this.\par
The version of ShaderGlass that comes bundled with this program is altered by me, and will not keep up with changes to the proper ShaderGlass app.\par
For clarity, the bundled executable is called \i ShaderGlassForShieldOfFaith.exe\i0\par
\b\fs28 MULTIPLE MONITORS\par
\b0\fs24 You could run multiple instances of shield of faith.\par
You could also use the two methods of the program (its own window and the ShaderGlass app) simultaneously, placing each on a different monitor.\par
If you run multiple instances, you may want to run each with a different configuration. You can create a shortcut for the program meant for each monitor, and use the command line options to give (at least one of) them a custom configuration file.\par
With its default settings, Shield of Faith records information to its config file when you close it, so that it will next start with a similar setup. (You can also manually edit them.)\par
\b\fs28 TIPS FOR TROUBLES\b0\par
\fs24 You could run into a situation where you have darkened the screen too much.\par
Certain parts of the operating system are not affected by this program, and will allow you to regain control in that situation:\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1 If you hold down ALT and press TAB, you get the program selector menu, which will not be darkened. Moving your mouse cursor onto a window in that menu, you should be able to find an X button to close the program. Shield of Faith will close its own ShaderGlass process if it has started one.\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}There may be communication issues between the two programs. Particularly if you make some manual adjustments inside the ShaderGlass app while it runs under Shield of Faith. Shield of Faith has a button to close the ShaderGlass app. Restarting the Shader Glass may help you regain control if something has gone confusingly wrong.\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}ShieldOfFaith stores info about its processes in a hidden folder on the disk and can use this information to emergency close all those processes. Unless there is a problem with this feature, the following methods can be used:\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Press the "Terminate all" button in the main interface, closing every shield of faith and every shader glass these have opened.\par

