BUGS\b0\fs24\par
I know of no outright bugs, but there are things that seem not to be possible, or within my ability:\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1 The basic screen cover in Shield of Faith seems not to work perfectly on Windows 11. After a Windows update there were complaints that the cover didn't feel quite as darkening anymore, and also that it won't reliably cover discord.\fs22\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\fs24 The presence of a translucent overlay window (the normal shield of faith implementation) has been observed to cause trouble with how Virtual Box reads the mouse for its virtual computers. There are probably other programs that do mouse handling in a way that doesn't work well with shield of faith covering them.\fs22\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}\fs24 ShaderGlass uses screen recording to render a darkened version of your desktop. (It can do more, but that is what Shield of Faith needs it for.)\fs22  This gives a very high quality recolouring, and it seems to be more reliable than the other method, but it has other problems.\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Shader Glass produces a yellow outline on the monitor. This is enforced by Windows. On Windows 10 it can \b not \b0 be disabled - according to ShaderGlass documentation.\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}In order to apply its effect to your mouse cursor, ShaderGlass must take over rendering of it. This means that when windows renders something that ShaderGlass is not allowed to cover, you will not see the mouse cursor. (You can choose to let the operating system render the mouse cursor instead, and then you can use windows settings to pick a suitable colour. I have gone for #999999 to get grey with dark outline.)\par
